Introduction ¶

Problem Area ¶

Fake news can be defined as inaccurate or otherwise misleading information that is growing both knowingly and unknowingly (Chen and Sin, 2013). With the rapid advancements in technology leading to the significance of social media to increase manifold, the online availability and hasty dissemination of ‘disinformation’ and ‘fake news’ have become a global threat over the past 10 years (Tucker et al., 2018).

Studies have shown that the spread of fake information on social media affects the reputation of many individuals and organisations (Cheng et al., 2020), while also causing mental and emotional stress (Began et al., 2005). Furthermore, Carson (2018) showed that most people in advanced economies would believe more fake news than truthful news by 2022.

Manual detection of fake news is a very reliable method. However it has limitations in terms of speed and it has become increasingly cumbersome and time-consuming due to the large volumes of content generated on the Internet. Such manual efforts can also be ineffective at times as fake news can be quicker to spread when compared to verified claims. This gave rise to false information recognition as an essential task in natural language processing (Throne and Vlachos, 2018).

To date, many automated misinformation detection architectures have been developed. While earlier methods use hand-crafted features based psycho-linguistics and n-grams (Perez-Rosas et. al., 2017) more recent studies rely on automatic extraction of relevant features in the form of distributed representations (Wang, 2017). Various machine learning approches are used in this field ranging from traditional supervised machine learning methods (Hossain et al., 2020, Khan et al, 2021, Vijjali et al., 2020) which classify the data as misleading or not by comparing the input text to an already existing corpora containing real and fake information (Elhadad et al., 2019) to state-of-the-art transformers (Morio et. al., 2020; Kar et al., 2020, Wu and Chien, 2020).

Objectives ¶

COVID- 19 is a contagious disease which caused havoc around the world. The pandemic is considered a global health crisis and thus a significant newsworthy event with related news being widespread on social media. Subsequently, misinformation has been especially prevalent during the ongoing COVID-19 pandemic, so much so that the World Health Organization (WHO) stated that the world was in a war to fight an "infodemic" along with a pandemic.

In light of the serious issue that surrounds COVID-19 fake news, this analysis aims to add to the ongoing research on fake news classification, focusing on COVID-19 social media posts to aid in the fight to curb the dissemination of fake news and support the spread of much needed factual information.

Fake news in relation to COVID-19 is a much bigger problem as it can influence people to accept and spread potentially deleterious claims and articles. For example, fake news claiming that alcohol is a cure for COVID-19 led to many deaths and hospitalisations in Iran (Karimi and Gambrell, 2020). Recent studies (Mazza et al., 2020) also show that there has been an increase in symptoms of anxiety and depression in connection with the pandemic, and as the spread fake news can be more successful when the population is experiencing a stressful psychological situation (Moscadelli et al., 2020), curbing fake news at the source and preventing it from spreading to a larger audience is crucial.

Dataset¶

The dataset used was that developed by Patwa et al. (2020) in connection with the ConstraintAI’21 shared task for Covid-19 fake news detection. The workshop was aimed to combat online hostile posts. The dataset was is freely available and was downloaded from the link provided. The dataset consists of 10,700 social media posts with predefined training (60%), validation (20%) and testing (20%) sets. Each dataset contains three columns; the id, textual social media posts and their corresponding label classification identifying whether the social media post is fake or real. The id is of type integer, while the social media posts and their corresponding labels are of type object.

The real news is collected from verified Twitter handles which give useful information regarding COVID-19 while the fake news were collected from various social media platforms including Twitter, Facebook and Instagram and verified to be fake by fact-checking websites.

Evaluation methodology¶

To determine whether the method is successful, the metric accuracy is used. Accuracy measures the number of correct predictions over the total number of predictions and thus calculates the percent you predicted correctly. This was chosen over other performance metrics like precision, recall and F1 as accuracy works well for single label, binary classification problems with balanced classes such as this one.

Data preprocessing is the phase of preparing raw data to make it suitable for a machine learning model. In this analysis it included the following steps:

  • The urls are removed and the words are deontracted. This is done as with many social media texts most words are contracted, which makes it harder for a machine learning model to recognise. Urls are also removed as they do not add significance to the analysis.
  • The tweets are tokenized into sentences and represented as a list of words. The tweets are also transformed to lower case and newline characters are removed. This is done due to the case sensitive nature of NLP libraries and to aid lemmatization in the subsequent steps as well as remove the noisey text that occurs when there is a newline character.
  • The tweets are lemmatized according to their POS tags to reduce the inflected words properly while still ensuring that the root word belongs to the language.
  • Special characters and stop words are removed. This is done as special characters are not readable and stopwords, i.e. the words that commonly occur in the English language usually do not add meaning to text.

#Defining stop_words
stop_words = set(stopwords.words("english"))

# Defining lemmatizer
lemmatizer = WordNetLemmatizer()


def decontract_and_deweb(tweet):
    
    """
    Reads in a raw tweet and returns the string without urls and with decontract words
    
    """
    # tweet is decontracted and urls are removed
    tweet = re.sub(r"won\'t", "will not", tweet)
    tweet = re.sub(r"can\'t", "can not", tweet)
    tweet = re.sub(r"n\'t", " not", tweet)
    tweet = re.sub(r"\'re", " are", tweet)
    tweet = re.sub(r"\'s", " is", tweet)
    tweet = re.sub(r"\'d", " would", tweet)
    tweet = re.sub(r"\'ll", " will", tweet)
    tweet = re.sub(r"\'t", " not", tweet)
    tweet = re.sub(r"\'ve", " have", tweet)
    tweet = re.sub(r"\'m", " am", tweet)
    tweet = re.sub(r"http(\S)+",' ',tweet)    
    tweet = re.sub(r"www(\S)+",' ',tweet)
    
    return tweet

def tweet_tokenizer(tweet):
    
    """
    Reads in a raw tweet and returns a list of sentences represented as a list of words.
    Tweet is also converted to lower_case and newline characters are removed.
     
    """
    tweet = tweet.replace('\\n',' ').lower()
    sentences = re.compile('[.!?] ').split(tweet)
    tweet_tokens = [sentence.split() for sentence in sentences]
    return tweet_tokens

def get_wordnet_pos(treebank_tag):
    
    """
    Converts a treebank POS tag to a wordnet POS tag.

    """
    if treebank_tag.startswith('J'):
        tag = wordnet.ADJ
    elif treebank_tag.startswith('V'):
        tag = wordnet.VERB
    elif treebank_tag.startswith('N'):
        tag = wordnet.NOUN
    elif treebank_tag.startswith('R'):
        tag = wordnet.ADV
    else:
        tag = ''
    return tag

def sentence_pos_tagger(sentence):
    """
    Takes a sentence as a list of tokens and returns a
    list of wordnet POS tagged tokens.

    """
    treebank_tags = pos_tag(sentence)
    wordnet_tags = [
        (treebank_tag[0], get_wordnet_pos(treebank_tag[1])) for treebank_tag in treebank_tags
    ]
    return wordnet_tags

def tweet_pos_tagger(tweet_tokens):
    """
    Takes a tokenized tweet and returns POS tagged tokens.

    """
    pos_tags = [
        sentence_pos_tagger(sentence) for sentence in tweet_tokens
    ]
    return pos_tags

def tag_lemmatizer(pos_tag):
    """
    Takes a POS tagged word and returns its Lemma.
    
    """
    if pos_tag[1] != '':
        lemmatized_word = lemmatizer.lemmatize(pos_tag[0], pos_tag[1])
    else:
        lemmatized_word = pos_tag[0]
    return lemmatized_word

def sentence_lemmatizer(sentence_tags):
    """
    Takes a POS tagged sentence and lemmatizes.

    """
    lemmatized_sentence = [
        tag_lemmatizer(pos_tag) for pos_tag in sentence_tags
    ]
    return lemmatized_sentence

def tweet_lemmatizer(tweet_tags):
    """
    Lemmatize tagged words from a tweet and flatten sentence nesting.

    """
    lemmatized_tweet = []
    for sentence_tags in tweet_tags:
        lemmatized_sentence = sentence_lemmatizer(sentence_tags) 
        lemmatized_tweet.extend(lemmatized_sentence)
    return lemmatized_tweet    

def tweet_clean(lemmatized_tweet):
    """    
    Takes a lemmatized tweet, drops special characters and stopwords

    """
    my_stopwords = stopwords.words('english')
    processed_tweet = [
        word for word in lemmatized_tweet
        if word.isalpha() and word not in my_stopwords
        and len(word)>1
    ]
    return processed_tweet

def tweet_processor(tweet):
    """
    Executes full data processing pipeline on a tweet
    """
    tweet = decontract_and_deweb(tweet)
    tweet_tokens = tweet_tokenizer(tweet)
    tweet_tags = tweet_pos_tagger(tweet_tokens)
    lemmatized_tweet = tweet_lemmatizer(tweet_tags)
    processed_tweet = tweet_clean(lemmatized_tweet)
    return processed_tweet

# Generating a word cloud for fake and real news

def disp_wordcloud(cloud):
    
    """
    Produces a word cloud with title
    """
    wc = WordCloud(width = 800, height = 800, 
                background_color ='white', 
                stopwords = stop_words,
                min_font_size = 10).generate(cloud) 
    plt.figure(figsize=(7,7), facecolor = None)
    plt.imshow(wc)
    plt.axis('off')
    plt.tight_layout(pad = 0) 
    
    if cloud == positiveCloud:
        plt.title('Figure 3: Real Social Media Posts Word Cloud', fontsize = 20)
    else:
        plt.title('Figure 4: Fake Social Media Posts Word Cloud', fontsize = 20)
    plt.show()
    print()

Baseline performance¶
Naïve Bayes is a classification method based on Bayes’ theorem that derives the probability of the given feature vector being associated with a label. Naïve Bayes has a naive assumption of conditional independence for every feature, which means that the algorithm expects the features to be independent which not always is the case.
Naive Bayes models the joint distribution of the feature X and target Y and then predicts the posterior probability given as P(y|x). Due to these characteristics, Naive Bayes is a very common baseline for text classification tasks, and the baseline used in this analysis. For the baseline, bag-of-words feature extraction is used.

SGD classifier¶
The Stochastic Gradient Descent used is a linear classifier (SVM) with SGD training. The gradient of the loss is estimated each sample at a time and the model is updated along the way with a decreasing strength schedule (aka learning rate).

Conclusions¶










Results Evaluations¶










The results of the above models can be seen in Table 3 below:


Table 3:¶

Tf-idf

Table 3 shows the results of different machine learning models on test dataset. Logistic Regression algorithm using the bag-of-words feature extraction performs the best, with 91.5 % accuracy. This is followed by the Stochastic Gradient Descent algorithm using the bag-of-words feature extraction with 90.9% accuracy. Bag-of-words feature extraction produced better results in all the models.


The experiments confirmed that all machine learning algorithms were successfully in beating the baseline model of Naive Bayes with Logistic Regression and Stochastic Gradient Descent outperforming the baseline with a difference of close to 2 per cent in accuracy .











Conclusion¶
In this work a simple but effective approach to COVID-19 fake news detection was proposed. Our pre-processing pipeline consisted of steps like stop word and noise removal, lemmatization and more. The classification approach  was based on machine learning models Logistic Regression classifier, Support Vector Machine, Stochastic Gradient Descent and Random Forest which were compared to the baseline of Naive Bayes. All models proved to be an improvement on the baseline and the work is reproducible.


Further work can include the addition of further linguistic features that can increase the predictive power of an interpretable model to match that of black box models. The work can also be expanded upon by collecting more data, enriching the data by providing the reason for being real/fake along with the labels, and collecting multilingual data.
